00:12:11.156 --> 00:12:12.046 A:middle
You want to double check

00:12:12.046 --> 00:12:14.446 A:middle
that everything you have
done is actually localized.

00:12:14.746 --> 00:12:18.256 A:middle
To do that, you can use the
new static analyzer in Xcode 8,

00:12:18.536 --> 00:12:21.576 A:middle
which will actually find
any issues that you have

00:12:21.616 --> 00:12:22.606 A:middle
with localizability,

00:12:22.606 --> 00:12:25.096 A:middle
where you're feeding
non-localized strings

00:12:25.196 --> 00:12:25.726 A:middle
into the UI.

00:12:25.936 --> 00:12:30.946 A:middle
And that's all there is to
localized strings, really.

00:12:31.076 --> 00:12:32.216 A:middle
Next let's talk about
formatters.

00:12:32.966 --> 00:12:37.326 A:middle
This is a common kind of
app that you see these days

00:12:37.326 --> 00:12:39.406 A:middle
with all the delivery services.

00:12:39.806 --> 00:12:43.976 A:middle
And this, however, is not a good
thing that you're seeing here.

00:12:44.326 --> 00:12:48.736 A:middle
So it says AM9:41, which to an
English user will definitely

00:12:48.736 --> 00:12:49.746 A:middle
look like nonsense.

00:12:50.186 --> 00:12:54.666 A:middle
But believe me, I've
seen this in a real app.

00:12:54.666 --> 00:12:57.456 A:middle
And similarly, you might see
something that is the opposite

00:12:57.456 --> 00:12:59.646 A:middle
in Chinese where
it puts the a.m.

00:12:59.646 --> 00:13:01.196 A:middle
/p.m. marker after the numbers,

00:12:59.646 --> 00:13:01.196 A:middle
/p.m. marker after the numbers,

00:13:01.196 --> 00:13:02.996 A:middle
which is completely
wrong for Chinese.

00:13:03.746 --> 00:13:06.986 A:middle
So how do we avoid
bugs like these?

00:13:09.116 --> 00:13:13.566 A:middle
The problem is actually
that we're using this method

00:13:13.566 --> 00:13:17.136 A:middle
which is formatter.dateFormat
setting a fixed format on it.

00:13:17.656 --> 00:13:19.266 A:middle
It seems like the
right thing to do.

00:13:19.696 --> 00:13:21.256 A:middle
It looks pretty nice in code,

00:13:21.646 --> 00:13:23.246 A:middle
but it's actually
the wrong approach.

00:13:24.406 --> 00:13:27.156 A:middle
And although it yields the
right result when you try it

00:13:27.156 --> 00:13:30.656 A:middle
out for English, so it'll give
you 9:41 a.m. you try the same

00:13:30.656 --> 00:13:33.016 A:middle
thing out in Chinese, and it
gives you the wrong result.

00:13:33.106 --> 00:13:36.466 A:middle
Why? Because it's applying
a fixed format to no matter

00:13:36.466 --> 00:13:38.776 A:middle
which language you're
running in.

00:13:40.076 --> 00:13:41.626 A:middle
The correct approach for this is

00:13:41.626 --> 00:13:45.536 A:middle
to just use the predefined short
style on the date formatter.

00:13:45.596 --> 00:13:47.916 A:middle
And it's going to give you
the right result for English,

00:13:48.966 --> 00:13:51.696 A:middle
for Chinese, and for any other
language your app might be

00:13:51.696 --> 00:13:52.286 A:middle
localized in.

00:13:53.326 --> 00:13:55.696 A:middle
And of course, there
are more styles.

00:13:55.846 --> 00:13:58.406 A:middle
So we have the short style
that I just showed you.

00:13:58.746 --> 00:14:00.996 A:middle
You can also get a
slightly longer style,

00:13:58.746 --> 00:14:00.996 A:middle
You can also get a
slightly longer style,

00:14:00.996 --> 00:14:01.836 A:middle
which has the seconds.

00:14:01.956 --> 00:14:04.176 A:middle
You can have a style
which has the time zone

00:14:04.636 --> 00:14:05.826 A:middle
or the full time zone name.

00:14:05.946 --> 00:14:08.056 A:middle
There are variety of different
styles for different needs.

00:14:08.706 --> 00:14:11.476 A:middle
And of course, not
just for times.

00:14:11.706 --> 00:14:14.246 A:middle
For dates, also, we
have the whole range

00:14:14.246 --> 00:14:16.226 A:middle
of styles going from
short to long.

00:14:17.396 --> 00:14:20.276 A:middle
Now you might come back to me
and say, "okay, sure but none

00:14:20.276 --> 00:14:21.976 A:middle
of those styles is
what my designer wants.

00:14:21.976 --> 00:14:24.796 A:middle
They want, you know,
just the full year

00:14:24.796 --> 00:14:25.936 A:middle
or just this or just that."

00:14:26.406 --> 00:14:26.906 A:middle
That's fine.

00:14:27.346 --> 00:14:30.106 A:middle
So you can use a format.

00:14:30.676 --> 00:14:32.756 A:middle
The important thing is to use it

00:14:32.886 --> 00:14:36.886 A:middle
with the setLocalizedDate
FormatFrom Template method,

00:14:37.146 --> 00:14:41.566 A:middle
which will make sure that it
takes your format, interprets it

00:14:41.626 --> 00:14:43.356 A:middle
for the current language
in question

00:14:43.596 --> 00:14:46.236 A:middle
and gives you the
correct localized format

00:14:46.236 --> 00:14:47.196 A:middle
for that language.

00:14:49.756 --> 00:14:53.946 A:middle
There are also two classes
that you might not have used.

00:14:54.166 --> 00:14:57.226 A:middle
They're fairly new, although not
new this year, date components,

00:14:57.226 --> 00:15:00.106 A:middle
which will let you format, say,

00:14:57.226 --> 00:15:00.106 A:middle
which will let you format, say,

00:15:00.326 --> 00:15:02.486 A:middle
a duration like 4
hours and 25 minutes.

00:15:03.536 --> 00:15:07.786 A:middle
Or a date interval like
the duration of this talk,

00:15:07.956 --> 00:15:11.886 A:middle
9 to 9:40 a.m. So the
advantage to these, again,

00:15:11.936 --> 00:15:14.026 A:middle
is that if you use
these classes,

00:15:14.466 --> 00:15:17.066 A:middle
all the localization is going
to get taken care of for you.

00:15:17.596 --> 00:15:23.746 A:middle
Next let's talk about
another kind of data type

00:15:23.746 --> 00:15:25.286 A:middle
that you can format, names.

00:15:27.616 --> 00:15:32.236 A:middle
Now, if this is how you're
going to show the user's name

00:15:32.236 --> 00:15:36.166 A:middle
or their friend's name to
them when they open your app,

00:15:36.166 --> 00:15:38.646 A:middle
they're going to get a really
bad impression of your app.

00:15:39.076 --> 00:15:41.346 A:middle
So let's not do that.

00:15:41.996 --> 00:15:46.336 A:middle
Instead, you should show the
names in the way that is correct

00:15:47.416 --> 00:15:49.126 A:middle
for that given language
and script.

00:15:50.466 --> 00:15:51.256 A:middle
So how do we do that?

00:15:52.736 --> 00:15:54.526 A:middle
It's actually really simple.

00:15:56.076 --> 00:15:58.986 A:middle
You create a
PersonNameComponents object.

00:15:59.116 --> 00:16:01.906 A:middle
Fill it with some name
components, and then just

00:15:59.116 --> 00:16:01.906 A:middle
Fill it with some name
components, and then just

00:16:01.906 --> 00:16:05.206 A:middle
like any other formatter,
you just ask for the string

00:16:05.376 --> 00:16:08.536 A:middle
from the components for any
given style that you want.

00:16:08.536 --> 00:16:11.096 A:middle
And again, we have a variety
of styles going from long,

00:16:11.446 --> 00:16:14.036 A:middle
which is the full name
all the way to abbreviated

00:16:14.036 --> 00:16:15.276 A:middle
which you can use for initials.

00:16:16.696 --> 00:16:20.056 A:middle
And of course, it supports
multiple languages.

00:16:20.586 --> 00:16:26.056 A:middle
New this year, though,
is name parsing support.

00:16:26.426 --> 00:16:30.186 A:middle
So now you can go from a full
name to a set of components.

00:16:31.196 --> 00:16:34.806 A:middle
And it's as easy as creating a
formatter, giving it a string,

00:16:35.256 --> 00:16:36.816 A:middle
and then looking
at the components.

00:16:37.336 --> 00:16:39.186 A:middle
If it returns nil, it
means it wasn't able

00:16:39.186 --> 00:16:42.816 A:middle
to successfully construct
components out of it.

00:16:43.756 --> 00:16:45.206 A:middle
The really cool thing, though,

00:16:45.206 --> 00:16:48.416 A:middle
is that this is not a
static API that's looking

00:16:48.416 --> 00:16:50.286 A:middle
at some set of static rules.

00:16:50.516 --> 00:16:55.026 A:middle
It's actually a statistical
model so that even if you pass

00:16:55.026 --> 00:16:56.716 A:middle
in the name in the
opposite order,

00:16:56.946 --> 00:17:01.666 A:middle
it knows that in John Appleseed,
John is much more likely

00:16:56.946 --> 00:17:01.666 A:middle
it knows that in John Appleseed,
John is much more likely

00:17:01.666 --> 00:17:04.695 A:middle
to be the given name and
Appleseed the family name.

00:17:04.695 --> 00:17:06.266 A:middle
And it's still going
to parse it correctly.

00:17:06.896 --> 00:17:11.806 A:middle
And of course, it supports
multiple languages as well.

00:17:14.175 --> 00:17:16.616 A:middle
So there are a lot
of formatters.

00:17:17.036 --> 00:17:19.536 A:middle
I talked about Date

00:17:19.906 --> 00:17:23.786 A:middle
and
PersonNameComponentsFormatters

00:17:23.786 --> 00:17:24.425 A:middle
in detail.

00:17:25.195 --> 00:17:29.626 A:middle
The components and interval
formatters for dates, briefly.

00:17:30.046 --> 00:17:32.646 A:middle
And there are some formatters
I didn't even mention

00:17:32.646 --> 00:17:36.026 A:middle
which are existing formatters
that we have in the system.

00:17:37.186 --> 00:17:41.686 A:middle
And there's the brand new
measurement formatter that's new

00:17:41.686 --> 00:17:43.406 A:middle
in this set of releases.

00:17:43.646 --> 00:17:47.436 A:middle
So be sure to use these
formatters wherever you can

00:17:47.436 --> 00:17:49.576 A:middle
in your code because they
will do the right thing,

00:17:49.576 --> 00:17:51.756 A:middle
and you will also save
localized strings.

00:17:53.136 --> 00:17:54.726 A:middle
Which you shouldn't be
using for these cases.

00:17:56.216 --> 00:18:02.396 A:middle
So that's all about at this
point your whole UI is localized

00:17:56.216 --> 00:18:02.396 A:middle
So that's all about at this
point your whole UI is localized

00:18:02.396 --> 00:18:03.116 A:middle
in terms of strings.

00:18:03.316 --> 00:18:05.646 A:middle
Now let's take a look at
what you need to do in terms

00:18:05.646 --> 00:18:07.316 A:middle
of the layout to make sure

00:18:07.316 --> 00:18:10.256 A:middle
that the UI actually works
well with those strings.

00:18:12.086 --> 00:18:16.256 A:middle
So the key word here
is Auto Layout.

00:18:16.616 --> 00:18:20.876 A:middle
It does what it's intended --
what its name tells you it does,

00:18:20.876 --> 00:18:22.646 A:middle
which is it automatically
lays things out.

00:18:23.246 --> 00:18:25.436 A:middle
And so whether you're
in a left-to-right app,

00:18:26.746 --> 00:18:30.706 A:middle
if you use Auto Layout you
will get automatically a user

00:18:30.706 --> 00:18:33.026 A:middle
interface for a right-to-left
language.

00:18:34.196 --> 00:18:38.276 A:middle
And again, Auto Layout is a big
topic, and I'm not going to go

00:18:38.276 --> 00:18:41.386 A:middle
into detail into how you
should use Auto Layout

00:18:41.386 --> 00:18:44.246 A:middle
because there are sessions
for that both this year

00:18:44.246 --> 00:18:48.326 A:middle
and from previous years that go
into a fair amount of detail.

00:18:49.756 --> 00:18:53.166 A:middle
What I will tell you is that
you should use UIStackView

00:18:53.166 --> 00:18:58.706 A:middle
and NSStackView as much as you
can because these are very easy

00:18:58.706 --> 00:19:01.466 A:middle
to use APIs that leverage
Auto Layout and make sure

00:18:58.706 --> 00:19:01.466 A:middle
to use APIs that leverage
Auto Layout and make sure

00:19:01.786 --> 00:19:05.616 A:middle
that your views will
flip in the right way

00:19:05.616 --> 00:19:07.996 A:middle
for right-to-left languages
and adjust appropriately

00:19:07.996 --> 00:19:09.966 A:middle
when they get long
and shorter strings.

00:19:11.056 --> 00:19:14.546 A:middle
So we will have sample code
for you that shows you how

00:19:14.546 --> 00:19:21.196 A:middle
to implement a version of the
Clock app using Stack Views.

00:19:23.046 --> 00:19:25.726 A:middle
Now one thing that you
might want to keep in mind

00:19:25.726 --> 00:19:29.096 A:middle
for layout is that sometimes
you need to get creative.

00:19:29.696 --> 00:19:31.446 A:middle
Now you see this
screen in English.

00:19:31.656 --> 00:19:33.526 A:middle
Are you sure you don't
want to use an Apple ID?

00:19:34.226 --> 00:19:37.846 A:middle
And you have two options there,
Use Apple ID or Don't Use.

00:19:37.846 --> 00:19:40.976 A:middle
Now in some languages you can
imagine the translations might

00:19:41.016 --> 00:19:43.616 A:middle
be longer than can fit in
two side-by-side buttons.

00:19:44.626 --> 00:19:45.756 A:middle
So what do you do?

00:19:46.146 --> 00:19:50.146 A:middle
Well, in this case, you see
that the whole view switches

00:19:50.146 --> 00:19:52.236 A:middle
to a top-bottom orientation
instead

00:19:52.236 --> 00:19:53.586 A:middle
of a left-right orientation.

00:19:54.196 --> 00:19:58.106 A:middle
And these kind of creative
UI elements are things

00:19:58.106 --> 00:20:02.596 A:middle
that you should keep in mind for
your apps before you ask a --

00:19:58.106 --> 00:20:02.596 A:middle
that you should keep in mind for
your apps before you ask a --

00:20:03.066 --> 00:20:07.726 A:middle
you ask a translator to
shorten a string to the point

00:20:07.726 --> 00:20:10.396 A:middle
where it might not even be
intelligible in that language.

00:20:14.176 --> 00:20:16.286 A:middle
The next thing is
vertical flexibility.

00:20:16.286 --> 00:20:21.076 A:middle
And a lot of you may not
have realized this before

00:20:21.076 --> 00:20:21.906 A:middle
for your apps.

00:20:22.936 --> 00:20:28.136 A:middle
So we have a lot of scripts
in the OS for languages

00:20:28.136 --> 00:20:32.776 A:middle
like Vietnamese, Thai, Arabic,
and Hindi that go much higher

00:20:32.876 --> 00:20:37.026 A:middle
or lower or both than the basic
Latin alphabet that's used

00:20:37.076 --> 00:20:37.936 A:middle
to write English.

00:20:39.336 --> 00:20:43.196 A:middle
And so what happens
often is we see this bug,

00:20:43.526 --> 00:20:46.366 A:middle
which is that somebody
might set clipsToBounds

00:20:46.366 --> 00:20:48.246 A:middle
to true on the label.

00:20:48.746 --> 00:20:52.126 A:middle
And what that does is it clips
the text often on both side

00:20:52.786 --> 00:20:59.156 A:middle
and besides being very ugly and,
you know, just looking terrible

00:20:59.156 --> 00:21:04.336 A:middle
in that language, you often lose
important semantic information

00:20:59.156 --> 00:21:04.336 A:middle
in that language, you often lose
important semantic information

00:21:04.336 --> 00:21:05.756 A:middle
like a diacritic mark.

00:21:06.376 --> 00:21:09.726 A:middle
In this case the pronunciation
of all of the words

00:21:09.726 --> 00:21:13.386 A:middle
on the right is changing
when you clip them like this.

00:21:14.566 --> 00:21:16.716 A:middle
So to fix this it's
pretty simple.

00:21:16.716 --> 00:21:20.106 A:middle
Don't set clipsToBounds to
true if you have a label.

00:21:20.716 --> 00:21:23.316 A:middle
And that should be enough
to solve this problem.

00:21:26.076 --> 00:21:29.706 A:middle
More interestingly, though,
when you have multi-line labels,

00:21:29.836 --> 00:21:32.846 A:middle
you also need to consider
interline spacing.

00:21:33.686 --> 00:21:36.856 A:middle
So let's take a look here
which has Hindi on the left

00:21:36.916 --> 00:21:38.736 A:middle
and English on the right.

00:21:39.896 --> 00:21:41.846 A:middle
And here it's English
on the left and Hindi

00:21:41.846 --> 00:21:43.246 A:middle
on the right, sorry about that.

00:21:43.906 --> 00:21:48.756 A:middle
But see what happens when
we try to squeeze Hindi

00:21:48.756 --> 00:21:51.796 A:middle
into the same amount of
vertical space as English?

00:21:52.506 --> 00:21:55.126 A:middle
It looks really cramped.

00:21:55.126 --> 00:22:00.546 A:middle
And any Hindi reader will tell
you this is really hard to read,

00:21:55.126 --> 00:22:00.546 A:middle
And any Hindi reader will tell
you this is really hard to read,

00:22:01.056 --> 00:22:02.536 A:middle
and it doesn't look nice.

00:22:04.026 --> 00:22:05.816 A:middle
So what you really need to do is

00:22:05.846 --> 00:22:08.866 A:middle
to give each script the
room it needs to breathe

00:22:08.866 --> 00:22:12.096 A:middle
and to look good on screen
and to be easy to read.

00:22:12.376 --> 00:22:14.656 A:middle
The good news is that
this is really easy to do.

00:22:15.946 --> 00:22:18.556 A:middle
Any time you have a
multi-line label, again,

00:22:18.696 --> 00:22:21.186 A:middle
a lot of this is done by default
but you just need to be sure

00:22:21.186 --> 00:22:23.416 A:middle
when you set a custom font
that you do the right thing

00:22:23.856 --> 00:22:27.256 A:middle
that you get a preferred
font using the UI font API.

00:22:28.626 --> 00:22:32.936 A:middle
Now, you might say, okay
I have a custom font

00:22:32.936 --> 00:22:34.636 A:middle
and I can't use this.

00:22:34.926 --> 00:22:39.056 A:middle
Well, there is a solution
for you, and you should check

00:22:39.476 --> 00:22:43.446 A:middle
out the fonts and typography
talk on Wednesday that goes

00:22:43.446 --> 00:22:45.776 A:middle
into more detail about
how you can make sure

00:22:45.776 --> 00:22:52.966 A:middle
that a custom font will
also adhere to dynamic type.

00:22:54.156 --> 00:22:58.966 A:middle
Next, for table views, we
do something really neat,

00:22:58.966 --> 00:23:01.716 A:middle
which is that if you have a
language with a taller script,

00:22:58.966 --> 00:23:01.716 A:middle
which is that if you have a
language with a taller script,

00:23:02.076 --> 00:23:07.536 A:middle
we will actually make the table
row height larger than it is

00:23:07.586 --> 00:23:09.136 A:middle
in other languages like English.

00:23:09.776 --> 00:23:12.596 A:middle
Again, this gives the script
the room it needs to breathe,

00:23:12.596 --> 00:23:15.936 A:middle
and it just overall looks more
natural for those languages.

00:23:17.196 --> 00:23:20.226 A:middle
The way you can take
advantage of this code is

00:23:20.226 --> 00:23:23.556 A:middle
by using the standard
UITableViewCell styles.

00:23:24.086 --> 00:23:26.976 A:middle
And now you might say, okay,
sure but I have a custom cell,

00:23:26.976 --> 00:23:28.706 A:middle
you know, it's not
going to work with this.

00:23:28.706 --> 00:23:30.776 A:middle
I mean, I don't just have
a label and you know,

00:23:30.776 --> 00:23:32.086 A:middle
it's not as simple
as you think it is.

00:23:32.086 --> 00:23:33.126 A:middle
And I'll be like, okay sure.

00:23:33.696 --> 00:23:37.466 A:middle
I agree. But what
I found at least

00:23:37.466 --> 00:23:42.546 A:middle
in using UITableViewCell is
that it is highly customizable.

00:23:42.856 --> 00:23:45.066 A:middle
It has a bunch of
overrides that you can use,

00:23:45.196 --> 00:23:47.436 A:middle
usually to get exactly
the appearance you want.

00:23:47.686 --> 00:23:51.406 A:middle
So try that first before you're
implementing a completely

00:23:51.976 --> 00:23:53.346 A:middle
custom UITableViewCell.

